You can chain array methods and pipe the result directly into `console.table()` to visualize transformations. For example:
javascript
const users = [
  { id: 1, name: 'Alice', active: true },
  { id: 2, name: 'Bob', active: false }
];
console.table(
  users
    .filter(u => u.active)
    .map(u => ({ name: u.name, id: u.id }))
);

This displays only active users with simplified columns, making it easier to verify the transformation logic.
